08161nam a22011535i 9783034611664DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20122011sz     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013946441  a97830346116647 a10.1515/97830346116642doi  a(DE-B1597)206368  a(OCoLC)979954768  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aszcCH 4aNA2750 7aARC0090002bisacsh04a720.282221 aSchröpfer, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaterial Design :bInforming Architecture by Materiality /cThomas Schröpfer. 1aBasel : bBirkhäuser, c[2012] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tWhy Material Design? -- tThe Alternative Approach: Observation, Speculation, Experimentation -- tDifficult Synthesis -- tAggregation -- tJoints and Junctions -- tWeaving: the Tectonics of Textiles -- tModulation: Transformation by Shaping and Texturing -- tCapturing the Ephemeral -- tResponsive Materials -- tMaterializations of Nanotechnology in Architecture -- tEncoding Digital & Analogue Taxonavigation -- tThe Future of Material Design -- tAppendix0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe approach of "Informing Architecture by Materiality" opens the way to an innovative use of materials in the design professions. Taking material qualities and properties such as texture, elasticity, transparency and fluidity as a point of departure, the concept described and employed here transcends the conventional definitions of building materials. Instead, the focus is on a multitude of material operations, like folding and bending, carving and cutting, weaving and knitting, mirroring and screening. The featured design strategies and methods address established and "new" materials alike. They are applied both to the scale of the detail and the entire building. The examples comprise prototype structures as well as large building projects. Eight chapters deal with surfaces and layers, joints and juctions, weaving and texturing, nanoscale transformations, responsiveness, the integration of ephemeral factors like wind and light as well as material collections providing professional resources. Written by reknowned experts in this field, the book features many examples from international contemporary architecture. The introductory part provides the conceptual background, while a final chapter describes consequences for pressing issues of today, like sustainability or life cycle assessment.  aWenn das professionelle Interesse an neuen Materialien über eine intuitive Faszination hinausgeht, stellt sich die Frage, wie Innovationen aus der Materialerforschung in die Architekturanwendung importiert werden können. Hier setzt dieses grundlegende Buch an. Ausgehend von Materialeigenschaften wie Textur, Elastizität oder Transparenz überwindet es die traditionellen Einteilungen von Werkstoffen zugunsten der Darstellung übergreifender Verarbeitungs- und Verwendungsarten wie Falten und Biegen, Schneiden und Weben, Spiegeln und Projizieren. Die entwurfsorientierten Strategien und Techniken umfassen sowohl die etablierten als als „neue" Materialien. Sie übergreifen alle Maßstäbe vom Detail bis zum Gesamtgebäude. Die Beispiele reichen von Prototypen bis hin zu großen ausführten Projekten der letzten Jahre. In neun Kapiteln werden aus dieser neuen Sicht Oberflächen und Schichtungen, Fügungen und Verbindungen, Gewebe und Texturen, Transformationen mittels reaktiver Materialien und Nanomaterialien, die Integration ephemerer Faktoren wie Wind und Licht sowie die systematische Erschließung von Ressourcen durch Materialsammlungen dargestellt. Einleitend wird die Herausbildung der aktuellen Materialkultur beschrieben. Ein abschließender Teil behandelt den Beitrag der Materialinnovation zu aktuellen Anforderungen von Fragen der Nachhaltigkeit, des Lebenszyklus usw.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitecturevDesigns and plans. 0aArchitecturexDesigns and plans. 0aArchitecture, Modernx20th century. 0aArchitecture, Modernx21st centuryxElectronic books. 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th century. 0aArchitecture, Moderny21st century. 0aBuilding materials. 4aDigital. 4aMaterial Design. 4aMaterial. 7aARCHITECTURE / Methods & Materials.2bisacsh1 aCarpenter, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, James.1 aFowler, Justin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Sheila.1 aLovett, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargolis, Liat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargolis, Liat.1 aMori, Toshiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMori, Toshiko.1 aSchröpfer, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTehrani, Nader, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTehrani, Nader.1 aViray, Erwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYeadon, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYeadon, Peter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Architecture, Design and Arts 2000 - 2014z9783110635690oZDB-23-GAA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Art and Architecture 2000-2014 (EN)z978311062112908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2010z9783110233544oZDB-23-DGG08iT